    %p
      %b <i>Candida albicans</i> as a model organism to study fungal pathogens and their interaction with the host

    %p
      The opportunistic pathogenic fungus <i>Candida albicans</i>, under usual circumstances, 
      is a harmless resident commensal in  human mucous membranes of a large percentage of 
      the population. However, taking advantage of weakened host immune defenses, for instance
      in immunocompromised cancer or AIDS patients, it may switch to its pathogenic status, 
      overproliferating and becoming thus the main etiological agent of candidiasis, one of the
      most prevalent and costly types of fungal infections in global terms.

    = image_tag  "colonization_and_invasion.png"

    %p
      Whereas the yeast forms may colonize healthy individuals mucous membranes, 
      in the case of immunocompromised patients, the hyphal form, usually associated
      to the pathogenic status, may penetrate into the tissue. Then a switch back
      to yeast form enables dissemination through vessels.


    
